{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476513"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:48:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:48:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13773"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13773"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.05,0.19,0.07,0.61]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6392"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55515"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6392"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13773"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41055"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"571"},{"type":"tags","id":"1317"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"3004"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12499"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18461"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42925"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44175"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55515"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy weighing 12 kg presents to the Emergency Department with his parent. The parent reports that four hours ago, they accidentally gave him 45 mL of paracetamol syrup (24 mg/mL) instead of the usual 15 mL dose. This equates to 1080 mg (90 mg/kg) instead of the intended 360 mg. They are worried about the overdose. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits: pulse rate 110/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There are no signs of jaundice or hepatomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Discharge home if well","Activated charcoal","Check paracetamol level and give acetylcysteine if detectable at eight hours post ingestion","Start acetylcysteine prior to checking paracetamol level","Check paracetamol level and compare to treatment nomogram at four hours post ingestion"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child has received an acute accidental overdose of paracetamol four hours ago. The parent accidentally gave 1080 mg (90 mg/kg) which is three times the intended dose. The recommended maximum daily dose is 60 mg/kg/day in children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the most appropriate next step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Echeck paracetamol level and compare to treatment nomogram at four hours post ingestion\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach is correct because we are dealing with an acute overdose that occurred four hours ago. The paracetamol treatment nomogram is designed for use in acute single overdoses and is typically applied at four hours post-ingestion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimply \u003Cstrong\u003Edischarging the child home\u003C/strong\u003E without investigating is inappropriate given the significant acute overdose. \u003Cstrong\u003EActivated charcoal\u003C/strong\u003E is also not indicated as it is too late after ingestion to reduce absorption effectively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChecking paracetamol level at eight hours post ingestion\u003C/strong\u003E is not the best approach in this case, as we have a known time of acute ingestion and can use the four-hour nomogram. The 8-hour rule is more applicable to situations where the time of ingestion is unknown.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option to \u003Cstrong\u003Estart NAC prior to checking paracetamol level\u003C/strong\u003E is overly aggressive in this case. While N-acetylcysteine (NAC) is the antidote for paracetamol toxicity, it\u0027s not necessary to start it before checking the paracetamol level in a situation where the ingestion time is known and the four-hour mark has been reached. The paracetamol level should be checked first and compared to the nomogram to determine if NAC treatment is necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, the most appropriate approach is to check the paracetamol level at four hours post-ingestion and compare it to the treatment nomogram. This will guide the decision on whether to administer acetylcysteine. Additionally, liver function tests should be checked, and the child should be monitored for signs of hepatotoxicity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The paracetamol treatment nomogram is used to assess the need for acetylcysteine in acute paracetamol overdose.","In acute paracetamol overdose, the paracetamol level at four hours post-ingestion is used to determine the need for acetylcysteine treatment.","The recommended maximum daily dose of paracetamol in children is 60 mg/kg/day (15mg/kg per dose, maximum four doses in 24 hours)"],"references":["Chidiac AS, Buckley NA, Noghrehchi F, Cairns R. Paracetamol (acetaminophen) overdose and hepatotoxicity: mechanism, treatment, prevention measures, and estimates of burden of disease. Expert Opin Drug Metab Toxicol. 2023 Jan-Jun;19(5):297-317. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37436926/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41055"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13773"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41055"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-16T12:25:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-16T12:25:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6392"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55515"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationsh